<task id="AUTHV2-020" project="Spaarke Auth v2 + Hardening">
  <metadata>
    <title>Migrate AiSessionProvider context to function-based API</title>
    <phase>B — Consumer migration</phase>
    <tags>auth, ai-widgets, react, FULL</tags>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-effort>2 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>Phase A complete</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>false (foundation for B)</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    AiSessionProvider currently exposes `token: string | null` in its context value (AiSessionProvider.tsx:99-104). This is the snapshot leak that caused the SpaarkeAi 401 bug. Replace with function-based API: { getAccessToken, authenticatedFetch, isAuthenticated, tenantId }. No token value in context.

    The provider also currently RECEIVES token as a prop from App.tsx — that prop is removed entirely. Provider uses useAuth() from @spaarke/auth internally.
  </prompt>
  <role>Senior React + TypeScript engineer.</role>
  <goal>
    AiSessionContextValue contains no token field. Provider internally uses useAuth() from @spaarke/auth. Every consumer that destructured `.token` will break compile and need migration (covered by tasks 021-022).
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.AI.Widgets/src/providers/AiSessionProvider.tsx</file>
      <file>src/client/shared/Spaarke.AI.Widgets/src/providers/useAiSession.ts</file>
      <file>.claude/AUDIT-FINDINGS-AUTH-SYSTEM.md §H-4 (this exact remediation)</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Edit AiSessionProvider.tsx: remove `token: string | null` from AiSessionContextValue interface. Add `getAccessToken: () => Promise&lt;string&gt;`, `authenticatedFetch: AuthenticatedFetchFn`, `tenantId: string`. Keep `isAuthenticated: boolean`.</step>
    <step>Remove `token` and `isAuthenticated` from AiSessionProviderProps. Provider gets them from useAuth() internally instead.</step>
    <step>Inside the component, call `const { isAuthenticated, getAccessToken, authenticatedFetch, tenantId } = useAuth();` and include them in the context value.</step>
    <step>Update useAiSession.ts hook return type accordingly.</step>
    <step>Run tsc --noEmit — every consumer that destructured .token will fail compile. Capture the list (will be addressed in tasks 021-022).</step>
    <step>Update AiSessionProvider unit tests to reflect new context shape.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>AiSessionContextValue has no `token: string` field.</criterion>
    <criterion>AiSessionProvider gets auth via useAuth() internally, not via props.</criterion>
    <criterion>useAiSession() return shape matches new context.</criterion>
    <criterion>Compile errors at consumer sites are the expected list (not unrelated breakage).</criterion>
    <criterion>Existing provider tests updated and passing.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
  <notes>
    Completed 2026-05-19. AiSessionContextValue now exposes the function-based
    contract: { isAuthenticated, getAccessToken, authenticatedFetch, tenantId,
    bffBaseUrl, ... } with no token string. Provider internally calls useAuth()
    from @spaarke/auth; props no longer include token/isAuthenticated.

    Tests: AiSessionProvider.test.tsx 24/24 + sse-event-routing.test.tsx 16/16
    (the latter was also renamed from .ts → .tsx to fix a pre-existing JSX
    parse failure under the current ts-jest).

    Jest mock for @spaarke/auth now exports useAuth (default: authenticated
    state with stub getAccessToken/authenticatedFetch/tenantId).

    Predicted consumer breakage to address in tasks 021/022/023:
      - src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/ChatHistoryPanel.tsx:155
      - src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/shell/ThreePaneShell.tsx:411
      - src/solutions/SpaarkeAi/src/components/workspace/WorkspaceLandingWidget.tsx:284
      - src/client/shared/Spaarke.AI.Widgets/src/components/FeedbackButtons.tsx
        (still defines `token: string | null` PROP — callers will fail to populate)

    AiSessionProvider.tsx now requires that `initAuth(...)` from @spaarke/auth
    has been called before mount (useAuth throws otherwise). SpaarkeAi already
    does this in App.tsx via authInit.ts (post-hotfix v2).
  </notes>
</task>
